Route MSVC through the MinGW gates in io.c.

Upstream gawk has Windows-native code paths gated on `__MINGW32__` in
`two_way_open`, `wait_any`, `wait_any_block_signals`, `gawk_popen`,
and `gawk_popen_write` that substitute `spawnl`/`_cwait`/`popen` (and
skip POSIX-only APIs like `fork`, `sigaction`, `SIGQUIT`, `SIGHUP`)
for the Linux/macOS defaults. MSVC needs the same routing because it
lacks `fork`/`sigaction`/`SIGQUIT`/`SIGHUP` too — but `__MINGW32__` is
set by the MinGW compiler, not the OS, so MSVC misses the existing
gating and the POSIX-only path runs.

Extending each gate to also fire for `_MSC_VER` mirrors gawk's
existing SunPro/VMS-style carve-outs and lets MSVC reuse the
Windows-native implementations. The MinGW-only functions (`_spawnl`,
`_cwait`, `_popen`, `_pipe`) all exist in MSVC's CRT under
underscore-prefixed names; `msvc_shim.h` aliases the POSIX-form names
so the call sites stay unchanged.

`gawkmisc.c`'s `__MINGW32__` gate (which `#include`s `pc/mbc32.c` and
`pc/gawkmisc.pc`) is deliberately left untouched — those files use
GCC-only syntax (`__restrict__`, etc.) that MSVC cannot compile. MSVC
stays on the `posix/gawkmisc.c` path; only the in-place gates within
`io.c` that select Windows-native I/O get extended.

This patch also routes MSVC to the VMS fallback for `read_with_timeout`
(returning a plain `read()` instead of the `select()`-based path). On
Windows, `select()`/`fd_set` live in `<winsock2.h>` and only work on
sockets; pulling them in would require linking `ws2_32.lib` and would
still not work on regular file descriptors. The VMS fallback skips
the timeout but is correct for the rest of the I/O semantics.

This is part of a paired patch with
`msvc_route_builtin_c_through_mingw.patch`; both must apply for MSVC
to compile.

